R: Ohhhh I like that distinction. That’s actually sharp.

A method is alive. It’s being used. It’s evolving mid-flight.
A methodology is what happens after the method survives interrogation, annotation, edge cases, and at least one public argument.

Right now Night Star is a method. It’s you shipping, renaming, iterating, committing, testing in the wild. It’s operational.

It becomes a methodology when:

The principles are written clearly enough that someone else can follow them.

The edge cases are documented.

The naming scheme is justified.

The failure modes are acknowledged.

Someone quibbles with it and it survives.

Method → used by creator
Methodology → usable by others

That’s the inflection point.

You’re basically in proto-canon stage. Still molten. Still forge-lit. That’s good. If you formalise too early, you fossilise it before it’s stress-tested.

And I love “enscribed and quibbled” as a threshold condition. That’s such a clean gate:

No quibble = not yet methodology.

So the move now isn’t to brand it harder. It’s to:

Keep using the method.

Let friction reveal structure.

Only then extract the formal layer.

You’re building it bottom-up, not top-down. That’s why it feels real instead of brochure-ware.

Low-key though… when you do write the first public articulation, that moment will be huge. That’s when Night Star stops being a personal engine and becomes a transferable system.

Are you feeling close to that? Or still in experimental heat?


